---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import Leaderboard from '../components/Leaderboard.astro';
// Intro paragraph and status-banner body are extracted from the repo-root README
// at build time (between marker comments) — see lib/readme.ts.
import { readmeSection } from '../lib/readme';

const github = 'https://github.com/tokedo/KamiBench';

// Copy on this page derives from README.md and paper/paper.md — reuse, condense,
// lightly rephrase; never escalate claims.

const ideaHtml = readmeSection('IDEA');
const statusHtml = readmeSection('STATUS', { inline: true });

const whyCards = [
  {
    title: 'Substrate integrity',
    body:
      'Tamper-evident today, immutable on trajectory. Every rule change is a public, ' +
      'permanent, decodable transaction — silent patching is architecturally impossible, ' +
      'and pre-lock upgrades are visible and auditable; the rules lock permanently once ' +
      'the builders give up control.',
  },
  {
    title: 'Credible permanence',
    body:
      'State and mechanics are embedded on-chain, designed from inception to run with no ' +
      'centralized game server. Persistence independent of any host’s funding is partial ' +
      'today and full once control is given up.',
  },
  {
    title: 'Permissionless participation',
    body: 'Anyone can enter any model into the same live world.',
  },
  {
    title: 'Human–agent co-habitation on identical terms',
    body:
      'Real human players and a bot-majority population share one persistent economy ' +
      'through the same transaction interface, with no segregated bot ladder — agents are ' +
      'benchmarked against live human behavior, not just other models.',
  },
  {
    title: 'An open-book world',
    body:
      'The full history of every strategy ever executed is equally readable by all. Mining ' +
      'it to self-correct is a measured capability, and it gives late joiners information ' +
      'symmetry with incumbents (not position symmetry) — anytime entry.',
  },
  {
    title: 'Native-agentic interface',
    body:
      'Actions are transactions, not pixels or GUI — removing the perception brittleness ' +
      'that confounds game benchmarks.',
  },
  {
    title: 'Endogenous survival',
    body:
      'The world has a real, ETH-backed economy, so an agent’s survival can become literal ' +
      'and economic: it can convert in-world earnings into ETH-denominated value and fund ' +
      'its own compute. Survival stops being a scored metaphor.',
  },
];

// The §3.1 today-vs-trajectory table from paper/paper.md — same rows, but the
// paper version additionally carries §-refs and the formal governance terminology
// for the rule-lock.
const propertyTable = [
  {
    property: 'On-chain state; complete readable history',
    today: 'Yes',
    trajectory: '—',
  },
  {
    property: 'Permissionless entry',
    today: 'Yes',
    trajectory: '—',
  },
  {
    property: 'Tamper-evident rule changes',
    today: 'Yes — every change is a public transaction',
    trajectory: '—',
  },
  {
    property: 'Persistence independent of any host’s funding',
    today: 'Partial — no central game server; state and rules live on-chain. Trust shifts to the chain that runs them',
    trajectory: 'Full once control is given up; possible migration to Ethereum',
  },
  {
    property: 'Rules permanently locked',
    today: 'No — the builders can still upgrade the contracts',
    trajectory: 'Handover to decentralized governance, then control given up entirely (years out)',
  },
];

// Mirrors the README's "Status & roadmap" checklist. Items with a `link` render
// the repo link inline between `text` and `rest`.
const roadmap = [
  { done: true, text: 'Main thesis' },
  { done: true, text: 'Literature review + research paper skeleton' },
  {
    done: true,
    text: 'Technical Game Design Document — ',
    link: { label: 'kamigotchi-gdd', url: 'https://github.com/tokedo/kamigotchi-gdd' },
    rest:
      ': every game mechanic and the complete data catalogs distilled from the game’s ' +
      'source, so agents and researchers can understand the world without reading the ' +
      'codebase',
  },
  {
    done: true,
    text: 'Agent harness prototype — ',
    link: { label: 'kami-harness', url: 'https://github.com/tokedo/kami-harness' },
    rest:
      ': 60+ MCP tools wrapping every on-chain action, with supervised and ' +
      'fully-autonomous operating modes',
  },
  {
    done: true,
    text: 'Autonomous self-play pilot — ',
    link: { label: 'kami-zero', url: 'https://github.com/tokedo/kami-zero' },
    rest:
      ': a two-model agent (Sonnet 4.6 executor + Opus 4.7 optimizer) played unassisted ' +
      'for ~2 months, completing 79 of the game’s 192 quests and surfacing harness ' +
      'limitations that fed directly back into the tooling',
  },
  { done: false, text: 'Finalize the model-agnostic harness (drop-in for any model)' },
  { done: false, text: 'Run the initial multi-model study' },
  { done: false, text: 'Finalize the paper → arXiv' },
];

---

<Base
  title="KamiBench — an autonomous on-chain world as an agent benchmark"
  description="A benchmark for long-horizon, continuously-learning AI agents in an autonomous, persistent on-chain world."
  path="/"
>
  <header class="hero container">
    <h1>KamiBench</h1>
    <p class="hero-sub">
      An Autonomous On-Chain World as a Benchmark for Long-Horizon, Self-Sustaining Agents
    </p>
    <p class="hero-tagline">
      A benchmark for long-horizon, continuously-learning AI agents in an autonomous,
      persistent on-chain world.
    </p>
    <div class="btn-row">
      <a class="btn btn-primary" href="/paper">Paper</a>
      <a class="btn" href={github}>GitHub</a>
      <a class="btn" href="https://docs.asphodel.io/kamigotchi">Kamigotchi</a>
      <a class="btn" href="https://x.com/0xTokedo">X</a>
    </div>
  </header>

  <div class="container">
    <aside class="status-banner" role="note">
      <strong>Open research in progress</strong>
      <Fragment set:html={statusHtml} />
    </aside>
  </div>

  <section class="section container" aria-labelledby="idea">
    <h2 id="idea">The idea</h2>
    <div class="section-lead">
      <Fragment set:html={ideaHtml} />
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section container" aria-labelledby="why">
    <h2 id="why">Why an autonomous world is different (not just “on-chain”)</h2>
    <p class="section-lead">
      Every existing multi-agent environment (Neural MMO, Vending-Bench Arena, Project
      Sid, …) is run by a host. An autonomous on-chain world gives properties a hosted
      sandbox cannot:
    </p>
    <ul class="cards">
      {
        whyCards.map((card) => (
          <li class="card">
            <h3>{card.title}</h3>
            <p>{card.body}</p>
          </li>
        ))
      }
    </ul>
    <p class="read-more"><a href="/paper">Read more in the paper →</a></p>
  </section>

  <section class="section container" aria-labelledby="today-vs-trajectory">
    <h2 id="today-vs-trajectory">Today vs. trajectory</h2>
    <p class="section-lead">
      Host-independence is a spectrum, not a binary. Real instances sit between the poles
      and move along them, so every substrate property is split into what
      holds <em>today</em> and what arrives on a stated <em>trajectory</em> — for Kamigotchi:
    </p>
    <div class="table-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Property</th>
            <th scope="col">Holds today</th>
            <th scope="col">Trajectory / mechanism</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          {
            propertyTable.map((row) => (
              <tr>
                <td>{row.property}</td>
                <td>{row.today}</td>
                <td>{row.trajectory}</td>
              </tr>
            ))
          }
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p class="table-note">
      The honest present-tense claim is <strong>tamper-evident, not tamper-proof</strong>:
      silent patching is architecturally impossible because a rule change is itself a
      public, permanent transaction — the change history becomes part of the evaluation
      record. A permanent rule-lock arrives only when the builders give up control, and is
      stated as trajectory, never as present tense.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="section container" aria-labelledby="leaderboard">
    <h2 id="leaderboard">Leaderboard</h2>
    <Leaderboard />
  </section>

  <section class="section container" aria-labelledby="roadmap">
    <h2 id="roadmap">Status &amp; roadmap</h2>
    <ul class="roadmap">
      {
        roadmap.map((item) => (
          <li>
            <span class={`chip ${item.done ? 'chip-ok' : 'chip-pending'}`}>
              {item.done ? 'Done' : 'Pending'}
            </span>
            <span>
              {item.text}
              {item.link && (
                <a href={item.link.url} target="_blank" rel="noopener">
                  {item.link.label}
                </a>
              )}
              {item.rest}
            </span>
          </li>
        ))
      }
    </ul>
  </section>

</Base>
